import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['num_dependencies'] = pd.to_numeric(data['num_dependencies'], errors='coerce')
    plt.hist(data['num_dependencies'], bins=20, color='blue', edgecolor='black')
    plt.axvline(data['num_dependencies'].median(), color='red', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1, label=f'Median: {data["num_dependencies"].median():.2f}')
    plt.legend()
    plt.title('What is the distribution of the number of dependencies?', wrap=True)
    return plt

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    source_counts = data['source'].value_counts()
    source_counts.plot(kind='bar')
    plt.title('What is the most common source in the dataset?', wrap=True)
    plt.axhline(y=source_counts.max(), color='r', linestyle='--', label=f"Max: {source_counts.max():.2f}")
    plt.legend()
    return plt

chart = plot(data)

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['num_dependencies'] = pd.to_numeric(data['num_dependencies'], errors='coerce')
    data = data.groupby('source').mean().reset_index()
    data = data.sort_values(by='num_dependencies', ascending=False)
    plt.bar(data['source'], data['num_dependencies'])
    plt.title('What is the average number of dependencies per source?', wrap=True)
    plt.axhline(y=data['num_dependencies'].mean(), color='r', linestyle='--', label='Average')
    plt.legend()
    return plt;
